+// Startup-phase overrides of the memory band. A game server's load-time peak
+// is routinely several times its steady working set — world generation and
+// asset streaming reach for everything at once — so a memory.high sized for
+// the steady state throttles exactly the phase that can least afford it.
+//
+// Worse, the damage is permanent. memory.min and memory.low only fend off
+// reclaim driven from OUTSIDE the cgroup, so reclaim a cgroup inflicts on
+// itself — by exceeding its own memory.high, or its own memory.max — ignores
+// them entirely. A ceiling below the load-time peak therefore evicts the
+// server straight through its own floor, and nothing pulls those pages back:
+// they return only when the workload faults them in again, one at a time.
+//
+// These variables state the band to apply while the server is still starting.
+// Wings replaces it with the steady band once the server reports ready, or
+// once the startup grace period expires. Only the memory band is staged:
+// cpu/io weights are work-conserving and cannot evict anything.
+const (
+	EnvStartupMemoryMin  = "WINGS_CG_STARTUP_MEMORY_MIN"
+	EnvStartupMemoryLow  = "WINGS_CG_STARTUP_MEMORY_LOW"
+	EnvStartupMemoryHigh = "WINGS_CG_STARTUP_MEMORY_HIGH"
+	EnvStartupMemoryMax  = "WINGS_CG_STARTUP_MEMORY_MAX"
+)
+
+// Phase selects which property band a slice should carry.
+type Phase string
+
+const (
+	// PhaseStartup is applied before the container is created and holds until
+	// the server reports ready or the grace period expires.
+	PhaseStartup Phase = "startup"
+	// PhaseSteady is the normal operating band.
+	PhaseSteady Phase = "steady"
+)
